T1  - MARRIAGE, MARKETS, AND MONEY: A COASIAN THEORY OF HOUSEHOLD FORMATION
AU  - Burdett, Kenneth
AU  - Dong, Mei
AU  - Sun, Ling
AU  - Wright, Randall
Y1  - 2016/05/01
PY  - 2016
DA  - 2016/05/01
DO  - https://doi.org/10.1111/iere.12160
T2  - International Economic Review
JF  - International Economic Review
JO  - International Economic Review
JA  - International Economic Review
SP  - 337
EP  - 368
VL  - 57
IS  - 2
PB  - John Wiley & Sons, Ltd
SN  - 0020-6598
UR  - https://doi.org/10.1111/iere.12160
Y2  - 2024/03/26
N2  - This article integrates search-based models of marriage and money. We think about households as organizations, the way Coase thinks about firms, as alternatives to markets that become more attractive when transactions costs increase. In the model, individuals consume market- and home-produced goods, and home production is facilitated by marriage. Market frictions, including taxes, search, and bargaining problems, increase the marriage propensity. The inflation tax encourages marriage because being single is cash intensive. Microdata confirm singles use cash more than married people. We use macrodata over many countries to investigate how marriage responds to inflation, taxation, and other variables.
ER  - 

TY  - JOUR
T1  - MODEL COMPARISONS IN UNSTABLE ENVIRONMENTS
AU  - Giacomini, Raffaella
AU  - Rossi, Barbara
Y1  - 2016/05/01
PY  - 2016
DA  - 2016/05/01
DO  - https://doi.org/10.1111/iere.12161
